We can add the following rule to \mu HOL^{ex}: 


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\Gamma  , \forall (\vec {y} : \vec {A}).\phi \,\vec {y} \Rightarrow  x\,\vec {y} \vdash  x\,\vec {\psi }$}
      \RightLabel {\small  $x \notin  \text {fv}(\Gamma )$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\Gamma  \vdash  \exists  \alpha  . (\mu ^\alpha  (x:T).\phi ) \vec {\psi }$}
    \end {bprooftree}


  which gives us an induction principle for \mu -formulae.

This rule is admissible in \mu HOL^{ex} if we add rules expressing that (anti-)monotone predicates on \text {Prop} are, in fact, (anti-)monotone with respect to derivability. For example, in the monotone predicate case:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , \phi  \vdash  \psi $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H}, P : \text {Prop} \to ^{+} \text {Prop} ; \Gamma , P\,\phi  \vdash  P\,\psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  These additional rules let us show that the following rules (critical for deriving the \mu -formula induction rule) is admissible:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , \pi \,\vec {y} \vdash  \chi \,\vec {y}$}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (mono)}
      \RightLabel {\small  $\mathcal {H}, x^+ : T \vdash  \phi  : \text {Prop}$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , \phi [\pi \,\vec {y}/x] \vdash  \phi [\chi \,\vec {y}/x]$}
    \end {bprooftree}

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , \pi \,\vec {y} \vdash  \chi \,\vec {y}$}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (anti-mono)}
      \RightLabel {\small  $\mathcal {H}, x^- : T \vdash  \phi  : \text {Prop}$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , \phi [\chi \,\vec {y}/x] \vdash  \phi [\pi \,\vec {y}/x]$}
    \end {bprooftree}


